line_items.description:
Organic

About this Coffee

Put the milk down. It's a special mule rule for the Yirgacheffe. These Oromia Co-operative beans are more floral than Grandma's Sunday best; an Arabica flavour so crisp and light that milk would just be wrong.

The farmers that grow it all indigenous to the area, working on organic, mountainside small - holdings to cultivate the potent flavours. So you owe it to them to drink it neat - to get the blast of sweet earl grey and citrus you're meant to.


Find us on Twitter and Facebook



  • Organic

  • Fairtrade

  • Strength - It will kick you this hard - 2

  • Ground zesty

  • Great taste 2014

  • For those who like to smell the flowers

  • Carried from oromia coffee farmers co-operative union, Ethiopia

  • With taste of earl grey & citrus

  • This bag is full of ground coffee


Usage


The Mule Rules

(A Quick Brewing Guide)

1. Choose your weapon

Grumpy Mule coffee are suitable for use in a wide range of brewing equipment. For espresso machines, finely grind your beans for best results.

2. Load up

Use 2 heaped dessert spoonfuls (those big ones your mum only had out for special occasions) of fresh, ground coffee per cup. If you want to be a nerd about it that's 15g per 250ml of coffee.

Espresso-heads, a good extraction time for our coffee is about 27 seconds per shot. Just don't count mississipily (watch Friends, it'll make sense).

3. Fire!

Allow heated water to come off the boil (about 93-95º) before pouring. It's just enough time to tweet a pic of the pack at a jaunty angle. Serve the coffee immediately once brewed.



Storage
Ambient


Looking after this coffee

Store away form direct sunlight and any strong odours - these beans have had enough sun thank you very much. And don't even think about putting it in the fridge.

Once open, squeeze out the air, seal the bag tightly and use within 2 weeks.



Grumpy Mule


Here is a Mule who wants to look on the bright side of things. He does. He's tried really hard to be that little ray of sunshine, to be fine with it all.

But he's not really that type. The mere sight of robusta beans or instant coffee crumples his brow and clenches his jaw.

After all, good coffee is never a matter of taking it easy - flavour doesn't just 'turn up'. It needs to be cultivated by expert growers, coaxed by obsessive roasters, and given the 'Hooves up' by the fussiest critic there is.


Roasted with pride in Meltham, Yorkshire

Usage


Simply: Add 200g of canned, drained tuna to the Tomato & Basil Pasta Sauce and heat together, stirring until bubbling. Serve with delicious Bay Tree Pasta.

Meal for Two: Place 150g of lean minced beef, 1 tbsp of chopped parsley, 35g white breadcrumbs, 1 egg, 1 crushed garlic clove, and seasoning in a bowl. Mix, shape by hand to make about 10-12 meatballs. Place in fridge for 30 mins (can be done in advance). Heat 2 tbsp of oil in a pan and fry meatballs until cooked. Pour a pack of the pasta sauce into a small ovenproof dish, warm in the oven at 180­°C, add meatballs, top with Mozzarella or grated Cheddar. Cook in the oven until cheese has melted and the dish is bubbling. Serve with Bay Tree Spaghettini pasta.
